            <fr:title text="Field">Field</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <html:p>A field is any set where the following properties hold.</html:p>
            <html:ol><html:li><html:p>Addition and multiplication of the elements is well defined.</html:p></html:li>
  <html:li><html:p>Addition and multiplication is commutative, associative, and distributive.<fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[a(b+c)=ab+ac]]></fr:tex></html:p></html:li>
   <html:li><html:p>The set must include an additive and a multiplicative identity.<fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[a+0=a\qquad \qquad  1a=a]]></fr:tex></html:p></html:li>
  <html:li><html:p>Every element must have an additive and a multiplicative inverse.<fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[a-a=0\qquad \qquad  a\frac {1}{a}=1]]></fr:tex></html:p></html:li></html:ol>
            <html:p>As an example, the rational numbers qualify as a field; the integers do not.</html:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:authors />
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2026</fr:year>
              <fr:month>4</fr:month>
              <fr:day>9</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:uri>https://andrewczezowski.github.io/forest/0003/</fr:uri>
            <fr:display-uri>0003</fr:display-uri>
            <fr:route>/forest/0003/</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Elementary Vector Space">Elementary Vector Space</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <html:p>A vector space is a set where elements can be added and scaled in a way that preserves structure. A vector is an element of a set called a vector space. We denote this set with <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {V}]]></fr:tex>.</html:p>
            <html:p>Not every set is a vector space so we need properties which define a set as a vector space.</html:p>
            <html:ol><html:li><html:p><html:strong>Closure Under Addition</html:strong></html:p>
  <html:p>The addition of two elements of a vector space will also belong to the vector space.</html:p>
  <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[\forall  v,w \in  \mathbb {V}, \exists \; v+w=s\in  \mathbb {V}]]></fr:tex>
  <html:p>Vector addition is commutative and associative.</html:p></html:li>
<html:li><html:p><html:strong>Scalar Multiplication</html:strong></html:p>
  <html:p>The operation of multiplying an element of the vector space by a scalar will yield another vector in the space.</html:p>
  
  <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[\forall \ v\in  \mathbb {V} \land  a\in \mathbb {F}, \exists \; av\in  \mathbb {V}]]></fr:tex>
  <html:p>Scalar multiplication is distributive and associative in both the scalars and the vectors.</html:p></html:li>
<html:li><html:p><html:strong>The Scalar <fr:link href="/forest/000G/" title="Field" uri="https://andrewczezowski.github.io/forest/000G/" display-uri="000G" type="local">Field</fr:link></html:strong></html:p>
  <html:p>The scalars that multiply the vectors are called the scalar field <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {F}]]></fr:tex> over which the vector space is defined.</html:p>
  <html:p>Real vector spaces are characterized by only having members with scalar multiplication my the set of real numbers. Similar for complex vector spaces.</html:p></html:li>
<html:li><html:p><html:strong>Linearity</html:strong></html:p>
  <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[\forall \ v, w\in  \mathbb {V} \land  a\in \mathbb {F}\rightarrow  a(v+w)=av+aw]]></fr:tex></html:li>
<html:li><html:p><html:strong>Identity Under Vector Addition and Scalar Multiplication</html:strong></html:p>
    <html:p><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[0+v=v]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[1v=v]]></fr:tex></html:p></html:li>
<html:li><html:p><html:strong>The Null Vector</html:strong></html:p>
  <html:p>Every vector space must contain the null vector. Additionally, every vector has its opposite.</html:p>
  <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[\forall \;v\in  \mathbb {V}, \exists \;w\in  \mathbb {V}\;|\;w=-v\; \land  v-v=0]]></fr:tex></html:li></html:ol>
            <html:p>
              <html:strong>Dimensionality</html:strong>
            </html:p>
            <html:p>A consequence of closure under addition and scalar multiplication is that any vector in the space can be defined as a linear combination of other some other vectors, this leads us to the concept of <html:strong>Dimensionality</html:strong>. The minimum number of vectors that could possibly describe any vector in that space. In other words the number of basis vectors. Dimensionality can be infinite.</html:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:authors />
            <fr:date>
